Restore the two remaining assembly blocks that did real work

An audit of every line still commented out by the assembly transformation found
two that were not timing padding but load-bearing logic.

AdLibService() reads the music as a stream of 16-bit chunks, and three assembly
instructions split each chunk into the OPL2 register address in its low byte
and the value in its high byte. Without them both variables were left
uninitialised, so every music event became a write of 0 to register 0. The
music engine ran correctly the whole time -- the right number of events at the
right tempo -- and delivered all of them to register zero. That is why the game
was silent even with a working synthesiser attached.

TimerInterruptService() accumulated the PIT divisor into a 16-bit counter and
chained to the saved BIOS handler only when that counter carried out. Summing
the divisor overflows 16 bits exactly once per original 18.2 Hz tick, which is
how the system clock keeps its own time while the game runs the timer at 140 or
560 Hz. With the assembly gone the BIOS handler was called on every single
tick, and the interrupt acknowledgement that should have been the alternative
branch ran alongside it rather than instead of it. Both are harmless while the
saved vector is a stub, and neither would stay harmless.

diff --git a/game2.c b/game2.c
index c68cb6d..6c7fa20 100644
--- a/game2.c
+++ b/game2.c
@@ -313,9 +313,12 @@ static void AdLibService(void)
 
         musicNextDue = musicTickCount + *musicDataPtr++;
 
-        // ASM: mov   dx,[chunk]
-        // ASM: mov   [chunkaddr],dl
-        // ASM: mov   [chunkdata],dh
+        /*
+        PORT: The assembly split the 16-bit chunk into its two halves: the low
+        byte is the OPL2 register address and the high byte its value.
+        */
+        chunkaddr = (byte)(chunk & 0x00ff);
+        chunkdata = (byte)(chunk >> 8);
 
         SetAdLibRegister(chunkaddr, chunkdata);
 
@@ -415,16 +418,29 @@ static void interrupt TimerInterruptService(void)
         }
     }
 
-    // ASM: mov   ax,[WORD PTR timerTickCount]
-    // ASM: add   ax,[WORD PTR pit0Value]
-    // ASM: mov   [WORD PTR timerTickCount],ax
-    // ASM: jnc   acknowledge
-    savedInt8();
-    // ASM: jmp   done
-acknowledge:
-    outportb(0x0020, 0x20);
-done:
-    ;  /* VOID */
+    /*
+    PORT: The assembly accumulated the PIT divisor into a 16-bit counter and
+    chained to the BIOS handler only when that counter carried out. That is
+    what keeps the system clock ticking at its own 18.2 Hz while the game runs
+    the timer far faster: the divisor sums to 65536 exactly once per original
+    tick. Interrupts are acknowledged only when the BIOS is not being called,
+    since the BIOS handler acknowledges them itself.
+
+    Note the WORD PTR in the original: only the low half took part, so the high
+    half is preserved here.
+    */
+    {
+        word previous = (word)timerTickCount;
+        word sum = (word)(previous + (word)pit0Value);
+
+        timerTickCount = (timerTickCount & 0xffff0000L) | sum;
+
+        if (sum < previous) {  /* carry out of 16 bits */
+            savedInt8();
+        } else {
+            outportb(0x0020, 0x20);
+        }
+    }
 }
 
